--- Hook triggered at 2026-07-02 19:08:38.711991 ---
{"session_id":"e5f7854c-c5bd-458f-8330-eb27e01ab0d6","transcript_path":"/Users/jakovivancek/.claude/projects/-Users-jakovivancek-Desktop-Jakov-Ivancek-projekt/e5f7854c-c5bd-458f-8330-eb27e01ab0d6.jsonl","cwd":"/Users/jakovivancek/Desktop/Jakov_Ivancek_projekt","prompt_id":"fccc6d59-d3eb-4542-8981-e94868eea343","permission_mode":"auto","effort":{"level":"high"},"hook_event_name":"Stop","stop_hook_active":false,"last_assistant_message":"Found and fixed the root cause. Here's what happened:\n\n**Root cause**: In `HotelDbContext.cs`, the `Service → Hotel` foreign key was configured with `DeleteBehavior.NoAction`, while every other child relation of Hotel (Rooms, Employees, Reviews, Attachments) uses `Cascade`. Since every hotel in your seed data has at least one Service attached, deleting almost any hotel trips a SQLite `FOREIGN KEY constraint failed` error — an unhandled exception, which is why you saw the generic Production error page.\n\n**Fix** (two files):\n- `Hotel-Mgt.Model/HotelDbContext.cs` — changed that FK to `Cascade`, consistent with the others.\n- `Hotel-Mgt.Web/Repositories/EfHotelRepository.cs` — `DeleteHotelAsync` now explicitly removes the hotel's `Service` rows before removing the hotel itself. This part matters most: your live database's schema was already built with the old `NoAction` constraint baked in, so the model fix alone wouldn't retroactively repair the existing DB file — the repository fix works regardless of what's already on disk.\n\n**Verified two ways**:\n1. Added a regression test (`Delete_Hotel_WithServices_RemovesHotelAndServices`) — passes, but I'll be honest that the test suite runs on EF Core's InMemory provider, which doesn't enforce real foreign-key constraints, so it wouldn't have caught this bug by itself.\n2. Reproduced the actual bug against a throwaway copy of your real `HotelDb.db` with `PRAGMA foreign_keys=ON` (confirmed the raw `FOREIGN KEY constraint failed` error), then confirmed the fix's exact delete sequence (services first, then hotel) succeeds cleanly with no orphaned rows.\n\nFull solution builds clean, all 58 xUnit tests pass.\n\n**This fix is only in your working tree — the live fly.io site is still running the old broken code.** Want me to deploy it now (`fly deploy`), or would you rather review the diff and deploy yourself?","background_tasks":[],"session_crons":[]}


